...Synopsis...
Another round of isolated thunderstorms is expected across the
Pacific Northwest this afternoon as a pair of weak upper-level
disturbances move into the region. This will pose a threat for at
least a few dry lightning strikes over dry fuels. Localized
wind-driven fire weather concerns are possible across northern
California, but weak winds elsewhere will mitigate additional fire
weather potential.

...Pacific Northwest...
Although drier air has begun filtering into the region, 00z observed
soundings and forecast soundings suggest lingering mid-level
moisture and gradually cooling temperatures aloft will support weak
instability by this afternoon. The general thermodynamic environment
appears similar to the previous 24 hours, which supported a mix of
wet and dry thunderstorms over OR. As such, a similar scenario is
expected today as a pair of weak upper-level shortwave troughs
(noted in water-vapor imagery off the CA and WA coasts) migrate
through the region. In addition to dry lightning strikes,
thunderstorms may produce strong outflow winds (see the Day 1
Convective Outlook for details). Precipitation over the past 48
hours has been sparse enough to maintain dry fuels over the region,
which will support another day of lightning-driven fire weather
concerns.

...Northern California...
Very dry conditions will persist across much of CA and into southern
OR today with RH values in the single digits to teens likely.
Although southwesterly flow aloft will increase somewhat with the
passage of an upper-level wave, the surface response is expected to
be weak with 10-15 mph winds likely across northern CA. Locations
that typically see terrain-enhanced winds will likely see periods of
elevated fire weather conditions, though this threat appears too
limited spatially and temporally to warrant highlights at this time.

