...Synopsis...
A more robust upper-level trough is forecast to begin moving onshore
across the Pacific Northwest through the day Wednesday. This will
bring another day of thunderstorm chances to parts of Oregon and the
northern Rockies, as well as strengthening winds across the northern
Sierra into southern Oregon where conditions have been dry.

...Pacific Northwest...
Forecast soundings continue to suggest sufficient mid-level moisture
will be in place to support weak instability east of the Cascades
and into the northern Rockies (though uncertainty in the western
extent of favorable moisture across central OR is noted). Modest
PWAT values near 0.6 to 0.8 inches and deep, well-mixed boundary
layers will support a mix of wet and dry thunderstorms. Similar
thermodynamic profiles are noted across parts of central ID and into
far southwest MT, but recent wetting rainfall over this region has
likely mitigated fuel readiness to some degree. As such, the
dry-thunderstorm risk area is confined to locations with receptive
fuels and sufficient confidence in thunderstorm potential. Further
refinement to the risk area is possible as confidence in the spatial
coverage of thunderstorms increases and fuels respond to warming
temperatures.

...Northern Sierra into Southern Oregon...
Southwesterly mid-level winds ahead of the main trough axis are
forecast to increase over northern CA into adjacent areas of
northwest NV and southern OR. While sustained winds will likely
remain near 15 mph, deep boundary-layer mixing coincident with the
increasing winds will support frequent gusts up to 20-25 mph
(possibly higher in terrain-favored locations). An increasing
downslope component will maintain dry conditions across the region
as afternoon RH values fall into the upper single digits and low
teens. With dry fuels already in place, elevated fire weather
conditions appear likely as winds increase.

